Beanstalk has three main string source forms and one character form.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    escaped_slice = "Hello\nworld"
    raw_slice = `C:\docs\site`
    letter = '🌱'

    name = "Ada"
    message = [:
        Hello, [name]
    ]
]

### Quoted string slices

Double quotes create escaped string slices. Escape sequences are interpreted by
the string literal parser.

### Raw string slices

Backticks create raw string slices in expression position. Their text is kept
without normal quoted-string escaping.

Inside a template body, backticks are ordinary body text available to the
active formatter.

### Characters

Single quotes create `Char` values.

### String templates

Square brackets create string templates. Templates produce owned strings and
may fold at compile time or lower to runtime string construction.

Templates own interpolation, formatting, slots, wrappers and structured
content. See @../templates (Templates) for the complete system.

Quoted slices, raw slices and templates all participate in the language's
`String` surface. Their storage and folding behaviour differs, but they do not
create three unrelated source-level string types.
